Only downside is that many questions have remained unanswered.  How come Frederick never aged in Asgard? What's with the two brothers being reborn or having no idea that their mother was a witch (who also never aged beyond 50, yet Dash and his brother do or do they?) And I never find out what Raven is up to or the implications of meeting Helena and meanings of traveller, bridge and dagger. I need another series!

Loved the Witches of East End and was so sorry it was cancelled after this second season. I don't think it ever found its audience. I have a few actual props from the series and when I told my daughters about them, neither of them had heard of the series :( which might explain its cancellation. Oh well, whether you are buying this to relive the episode, or are new to this little gem of a series; I strongly urge you to buy the series on DVD; the woman are all gorgeous, the men quite handsome, and the goings-on are mysterious & intriguing.

I love this series and wish it wasn't being cancelled! This series (in my opinion)is far better than other witch series out there like Charmed. That being said, the Charmed series lasted for 8 plus seasons. I see so much potential and hate to see Witches of East End cut early. I agree with the other review and hope another network is able to pick this series up and give it the run it deserves.

PROs Season 2 was just plain better than season 1, although some viewers left the show because it got "too dark". I'm glad WoEE wasn't afraid to depart into darker territory rather than turning into Bewitched. The addition of James Marsters (Spike from Buffy/Angel) as Tarkoff in ep 7 (Art of Darkness) was a righteous casting choice. Aging Buffy the Vampire Slayer fans out there (like me) may appreciate WoEE even more due to Marsters being a recurring character. This season the Beauchamp family characters were more comfortable in their skins, and seemingly with one another as actors. It's more apparent than ever that Mdchen Amick was born for this role; Rachel Boston makes a strong showing as well. I'm a vampire cognoscente, but WoEE and Salem have caused me to keep an eye out for more witch serials. WoEE features fewer petulant characters than the middling Vampire Diaries, and best of all: no rotten stinkin' werewolves. CONs Despite decent sets and slick production values, WoEE falls well short of an HBO classic like True Blood, mostly due to the script. I really could have done without the Scarface/disco flashbacks in ep 5 (Boogie Knight). No extras or bonus/special features: this is the primary shortcoming of Amazon's CreateSpace DVDs (manufactured on demand when ordered from Amazon). On the plus side, "by eliminating inventory, waste, and inefficiencies in the distribution system, on-demand manufacturing provides the added benefit of helping preserve the environment." Look at the cover art for this DVD: why does it feature our heroines dressed as street corner harlots? Still a bit hokey at times, but it kept me coming back. Unfortunately the show got cancelled, so this was the final season
It needs picked up, show is too great for it to be over... Bring this show back, seriously the rating and the market it would pull in, it's on a level above charmed!

A delightful, mildly trashy show with plenty of heart and a superb cast. Witches of East End deserved far better treatment than being cancelled after its second season, which left viewers with many unanswered questions. Perhaps another network will be shrewd enough to give it a further season or two, so it can become the cult-classic it deserves to be.
